03907nam a22005895i 9780300132960DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001329607 a10.12987/97803001329602doi  a(DE-B1597)485306  a(OCoLC)952732131  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aJN5450b.G6313 2000eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a945.0912211 aGobetti, Piero, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Liberal Revolution /cPiero Gobetti; ed. by Nadia Urbinati. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aItalian Literature and Thought0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is the first English-language edition of a collection of writings by one of Italy’s most important radical liberals, Piero Gobetti (1901-1926). In thirty-five thought-provoking essays, Gobetti proposes an original and challenging notion of liberalism as a revolutionary theory of both the individual and social and political movements. His theory is of particular relevance in the wake of the collapse of Marxist socialism, as non-Western countries with nonliberal or antiliberal cultural and moral traditions confront the problems of transition toward democracy and liberalism. Gobetti’s ideas continue to influence in important ways today’s heated debates over the nature of liberalism.Gobetti was the first Italian scholar to identify “two Italys”: one enlightened and modern though small and weak, the other premodern, traditional, and dominant. A witness to the seizure of power by the Fascists, Gobetti became convinced that Italy’s hostility to liberalism could be overcome only with a cultural revolution. Endorsing a radical liberalism, he nevertheless believed that the Communists, led by Antonio Gramsci, could play a crucial role in democratizing Italy by helping to develop a secular culture. For a liberal state to subsist and grow, Gobetti argued, there must first be a transformation of both the economic structure and the legal and moral culture of the society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAnti-fascist movementsxSourcesxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aAnti-fascist movementszItalyxHistoryy20th centuryvSources. 0aLiberalismxSourcesxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aLiberalismzItalyxHistoryy20th centuryvSources. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBobbio, Norberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCuaig, William.1 aUrbinati, Nadia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013296040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300132960423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300132960/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles